Message(content='```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can we create large-scale graph datasets with sufficient labeled data to effectively train and evaluate Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) for supervised learning tasks, particularly multi-label classification problems?",\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Addressing this problem is crucial for advancing GNN research and applications. Sufficiently labeled large-scale datasets will enable more robust training of GNNs, leading to better generalization and performance. This will facilitate the development of more accurate models for real-world applications such as fraud detection, recommendation systems, and molecular structure prediction. Additionally, it will support systematic evaluation of GNN scalability and efficiency, driving future research in this field.",\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "Creating large-scale graph datasets with sufficient labeled data is challenging due to the proprietary nature of most large graph data and the difficulty in generating high-quality synthetic labels. Naive approaches, such as using existing small datasets with limited labels, may lead to overfitting and poor generalization. Technical obstacles include the need for efficient data generation and labeling techniques, while theoretical challenges involve understanding the impact of label scarcity on model performance.",\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has focused on creating large graph datasets with minimal labeled data, such as OGBN and MAG, which only provide about 1% labeled nodes. These datasets are insufficient for training GNNs effectively for supervised learning tasks. The gap lies in the lack of methodologies for generating or obtaining large-scale labeled datasets. Our approach will differ by developing novel techniques for data augmentation and semi-supervised learning to create more comprehensive datasets.",\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "Our approach involves developing a data augmentation framework that can generate synthetic labels for large graph datasets while maintaining data integrity. We will use semi-supervised learning techniques to improve the quality of these labels. The key dataset will be a combination of existing large graph datasets with our generated labels. Metrics will include model accuracy, generalization performance, and computational efficiency. Expected outcomes include a new large-scale labeled graph dataset and improved GNN models that perform better on unseen data."\n}\n```', role='assistant', tool_calls=None, function_call=None, provider_specific_fields=None)
