These are your memory: {"type": "action_response", "result": "### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe primary challenge in Graph Neural Network (GNN) research is the lack of large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data. Existing datasets, such as OGBN and MAG, are large but contain very limited labeled data, which hinders the training of GNNs for tasks that require large amounts of labeled data, such as multi-label classification.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- **OGBN and MAG:** These are large graph benchmark suites that provide up to 244 million nodes and 1.7 billion edges. They are widely used for benchmarking GNN performance.\n- **Li-ArcFace:** A novel loss function for enhancing face recognition performance.\n- **FastGL:** A GPU-efficient framework for accelerating sampling-based training of GNNs on large-scale graphs.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- **Lack of Labeled Data:** Most existing datasets have a very small proportion of labeled nodes, making it difficult to train GNNs effectively for tasks requiring large amounts of labeled data.\n- **Scalability and Flexibility:** There is a need for datasets that provide sub-datasets of varying graph sizes and embeddings, maintaining consistent homophily, and offering a range of multi-class classification tasks with varying degrees of complexity.\n- **System Scalability:** Frameworks and systems need to be evaluated across different dataset sizes to understand their scalability and performance requirements.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Dataset Augmentation Techniques:**\n   - Develop techniques to augment existing datasets with synthetic labeled data to increase the amount of available labeled data for training GNNs.\n\n2. **Flexible Dataset Generation:**\n   - Create a tool or framework that can generate flexible datasets with varying graph sizes, embeddings, and homophily levels, allowing researchers to systematically evaluate GNN models.\n\n3. **Transfer Learning for GNNs:**\n   - Explore transfer learning methods that can leverage pre-trained GNN models on large-scale datasets to improve performance on smaller datasets with limited labeled data.\n\n4. **Scalable GNN Frameworks:**\n   - Develop scalable GNN frameworks that can efficiently handle large graph datasets and provide insights into system requirements and performance across different dataset sizes.\n\n5. **Evaluation Metrics:**\n   - Propose new evaluation metrics that can better assess the performance of GNN models on datasets with varying sizes and complexities.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe main gaps identified are the lack of large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data and the need for flexible datasets that can be used to systematically evaluate GNN models. Potential research ideas include dataset augmentation techniques, flexible dataset generation, transfer learning methods, scalable GNN frameworks, and new evaluation metrics.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nGraph Neural Networks (GNNs) are powerful tools for processing graph-structured data but face significant challenges due to the lack of large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data. This limits their effectiveness in real-world applications.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we generate flexible and scalable graph datasets with sufficient labeled data to improve the training and evaluation of Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem will enable researchers to train more effective GNN models for a wide range of applications, including fraud detection, recommendation systems, and molecular structure prediction. It will also facilitate systematic evaluation of GNN models across different dataset sizes and complexities, advancing the field of deep learning.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nCreating large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data is challenging due to the proprietary nature of most graph data. Additionally, generating flexible datasets that maintain consistent homophily and provide a range of multi-class classification tasks with varying degrees of complexity is technically demanding.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on developing large graph benchmark suites like OGBN and MAG, but these datasets lack sufficient labeled data. There is a need for innovative techniques to augment existing datasets and generate flexible datasets, which has not been fully addressed in the literature.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a tool for generating flexible graph datasets with varying graph sizes, embeddings, and homophily levels, and sufficient labeled data. The tool will leverage existing datasets and synthetic data generation techniques. Evaluation metrics will be proposed to assess the performance of GNN models on these datasets. Expected outcomes include improved GNN models and a better understanding of system requirements and performance across different dataset sizes and complexities."}

