['agent1 (agent1 collaborate with agent3 - I am a researcher specializing in deep imitation learning and its applications in autonomous driving, with a particular focus on navigating complex environments like crowded intersections. My recent work has led to the development of a multi-task conditional imitation learning framework that enhances both lateral and longitudinal control tasks, significantly improving interaction safety with pedestrians. I also created the IntersectNav benchmark, which provides human demonstrations to facilitate research in this area.\n\nIn addition to my work on imitation learning, I have conducted a comprehensive survey of deep reinforcement learning (DRL) and deep imitation learning (DIL) techniques for deriving driving policies in autonomous vehicles. This survey not only categorizes existing literature but also addresses critical issues such as driving safety and environmental uncertainty, providing insights that can guide future research.\n\nMoreover, I have explored the realm of remote sensing image processing, specifically focusing on pansharpening. I developed a novel probability-based global cross-modal upsampling method (PGCU) that leverages both local and global information from low-resolution multispectral images and guiding panchromatic images. My experiments demonstrate that PGCU outperforms existing methods and enhances the performance of state-of-the-art deep learning approaches in pansharpening.\n\nThrough my research, I aim to bridge the gap between advanced machine learning techniques and real-world applications, contributing to safer and more efficient autonomous systems.)', 'agent2 (agent2 collaborate with agent3 - I am a researcher dedicated to advancing the efficiency and effectiveness of deep neural networks (DNNs) in computer vision and related fields. My work primarily focuses on optimizing DNNs for deployment on resource-constrained devices, such as smartphones, where computational intensity and memory usage pose significant challenges. \n\nIn my recent publications, I introduced Fixed-point Factorized Networks (FFNs) to reduce computational complexity while maintaining accuracy, and developed Binary Weight Networks via Hashing (BWNH) to enhance performance with low-bit representations. I also explored innovative quantization techniques, such as the Q-ViT framework for vision transformers, which allows for learnable quantization parameters, and the Soft Threshold Ternary Networks (STTN) that automatically determine quantization intervals.\n\nMy research extends to the realm of privacy in machine learning, where I proposed frameworks that balance user-level differential privacy with model performance, and I have investigated the integration of location information into semantic segmentation tasks to improve accuracy. Additionally, I am exploring zero-shot transfer learning in graph data, introducing the ZeroG framework to facilitate cross-dataset generalization.\n\nThrough my work, I aim to bridge the gap between cutting-edge deep learning techniques and practical applications, ensuring that advanced models can be effectively utilized in real-world scenarios. I am passionate about pushing the boundaries of what is possible in machine learning while maintaining a focus on efficiency and accessibility.)', 'agent4 (agent3 collaborate with agent4 - I am a researcher specializing in differential geometry and mathematical physics, with a particular focus on Riemannian manifolds and their curvature properties. My recent work has explored the compactness of metrics in conformal classes with prescribed positive $Q$-curvature, demonstrating significant results in dimensions 5, 6, and 7. I have developed flow approaches to tackle the generalized Loewner-Nirenberg problem, establishing unique solutions to the $\\sigma_k$-Ricci equation on compact manifolds with boundary.\n\nMy research also delves into the uniqueness of conformally compact Einstein metrics, particularly for Berger metrics on spheres and their higher-dimensional analogs. I have shown that these metrics are unique up to isometries, contributing to our understanding of the relationship between curvature and conformal structures. Additionally, I have investigated the existence of asymptotically hyperbolic metrics and their implications in spectral theory.\n\nBeyond geometry, I have ventured into the realm of condensed matter physics, studying correlated electron systems and the Kondo-Lattice model. My work employs advanced computational techniques, such as the dual-fermion approach, to analyze the effects of spatial fluctuations in these systems.\n\nOverall, my research aims to bridge the gap between abstract mathematical theories and their practical applications in physics, providing insights that advance both fields. I am passionate about exploring the intricate connections between geometry, topology, and physical phenomena, and I look forward to further contributions in these areas.)', 'agent5 (agent3 collaborate with agent5 - I am a researcher dedicated to enhancing the efficiency and performance of neural networks, particularly in the context of approximate computing and graph neural networks (GNNs). My recent work has focused on developing innovative architectures and methodologies that address the challenges of energy efficiency, computational redundancy, and memory consumption in deep learning applications.\n\nOne of my notable contributions is AXNet, a unified neural network structure that integrates approximators and predictors into a single end-to-end trainable model, significantly improving invocation rates and reducing training time. I also introduced the Multiclass-Classifier and Multiple Approximators (MCMA) architecture, which optimizes the invocation of approximators for better energy efficiency.\n\nIn the realm of GNNs, I have developed FastGL, a GPU-efficient framework that accelerates sampling-based training by optimizing memory I/O, computation, and subgraph sampling phases. My work on the Memory-Efficient GNN Accelerator (MEGA) further explores algorithm-hardware co-design, employing degree-aware mixed-precision quantization to enhance performance while minimizing memory usage.\n\nAdditionally, I have investigated the potential of resistive random-access memory (ReRAM) for deep learning, proposing novel architectures that leverage its in-memory computing capabilities to improve training efficiency and robustness against weight drifting.\n\nThrough my research, I aim to bridge the gap between theoretical advancements and practical applications, ensuring that deep learning technologies can be effectively deployed in resource-constrained environments. My work not only contributes to the academic community but also has the potential to impact real-world applications across various domains.)', 'agent6 (agent3 collaborate with agent6 - I am a researcher dedicated to advancing the fields of deep learning and computer vision, with a particular focus on optimizing neural network architectures for efficiency and performance. My recent work includes the development of Fixed-point Factorized Networks (FFN), which significantly reduce computational complexity and storage requirements for deep neural networks, making them more suitable for embedded systems like smartphones. \n\nI have also tackled the challenges of visible-thermal cross-modality person re-identification (VT Re-ID) by proposing an approach that enhances discriminative feature learning through innovative techniques such as skip-connections and dual-modality triplet loss. My research extends to super-resolution, where I introduced a probabilistic model that improves image restoration by addressing the non-uniqueness of high-resolution candidates.\n\nIn the realm of time series classification, I developed the Self-Attentive Recurrent Convolutional Networks (SARCoN), which effectively learn multi-faceted representations and provide interpretability in identifying key features. Additionally, I have explored reinforcement learning for adaptive control in electric and connected vehicles, demonstrating significant energy savings while maintaining travel efficiency.\n\nMy work in federated learning has led to the creation of a Hyperparameter Network (HPN) that personalizes hyperparameter choices for heterogeneous clients while preserving data privacy. I have also contributed to probabilistic inference in Bayesian networks through innovative sampling algorithms, enhancing the precision of posterior probability estimates.\n\nOverall, my research aims to bridge the gap between advanced machine learning techniques and practical applications, ensuring that these technologies are both effective and accessible in real-world scenarios.)']But you do not have to communcate with other agents.
You can also solve the task by calling other functions to solve it by yourself.
These are your memory: {"type": "action_response", "result": "### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe primary challenge in Graph Neural Network (GNN) research is the lack of large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data. Existing datasets, such as OGBN and MAG, are large but contain very limited labeled data, which hinders the training of GNNs for tasks that require large amounts of labeled data, such as multi-label classification.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- **OGBN and MAG:** These are large graph benchmark suites that provide up to 244 million nodes and 1.7 billion edges. They are widely used for benchmarking GNN performance.\n- **Li-ArcFace:** A novel loss function for enhancing face recognition performance.\n- **FastGL:** A GPU-efficient framework for accelerating sampling-based training of GNNs on large-scale graphs.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- **Lack of Labeled Data:** Most existing datasets have a very small proportion of labeled nodes, making it difficult to train GNNs effectively for tasks requiring large amounts of labeled data.\n- **Scalability and Flexibility:** There is a need for datasets that provide sub-datasets of varying graph sizes and embeddings, maintaining consistent homophily, and offering a range of multi-class classification tasks with varying degrees of complexity.\n- **System Scalability:** Frameworks and systems need to be evaluated across different dataset sizes to understand their scalability and performance requirements.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Dataset Augmentation Techniques:**\n   - Develop techniques to augment existing datasets with synthetic labeled data to increase the amount of available labeled data for training GNNs.\n\n2. **Flexible Dataset Generation:**\n   - Create a tool or framework that can generate flexible datasets with varying graph sizes, embeddings, and homophily levels, allowing researchers to systematically evaluate GNN models.\n\n3. **Transfer Learning for GNNs:**\n   - Explore transfer learning methods that can leverage pre-trained GNN models on large-scale datasets to improve performance on smaller datasets with limited labeled data.\n\n4. **Scalable GNN Frameworks:**\n   - Develop scalable GNN frameworks that can efficiently handle large graph datasets and provide insights into system requirements and performance across different dataset sizes.\n\n5. **Evaluation Metrics:**\n   - Propose new evaluation metrics that can better assess the performance of GNN models on datasets with varying sizes and complexities.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe main gaps identified are the lack of large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data and the need for flexible datasets that can be used to systematically evaluate GNN models. Potential research ideas include dataset augmentation techniques, flexible dataset generation, transfer learning methods, scalable GNN frameworks, and new evaluation metrics.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nGraph Neural Networks (GNNs) are powerful tools for processing graph-structured data but face significant challenges due to the lack of large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data. This limits their effectiveness in real-world applications.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we generate flexible and scalable graph datasets with sufficient labeled data to improve the training and evaluation of Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem will enable researchers to train more effective GNN models for a wide range of applications, including fraud detection, recommendation systems, and molecular structure prediction. It will also facilitate systematic evaluation of GNN models across different dataset sizes and complexities, advancing the field of deep learning.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nCreating large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data is challenging due to the proprietary nature of most graph data. Additionally, generating flexible datasets that maintain consistent homophily and provide a range of multi-class classification tasks with varying degrees of complexity is technically demanding.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on developing large graph benchmark suites like OGBN and MAG, but these datasets lack sufficient labeled data. There is a need for innovative techniques to augment existing datasets and generate flexible datasets, which has not been fully addressed in the literature.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a tool for generating flexible graph datasets with varying graph sizes, embeddings, and homophily levels, and sufficient labeled data. The tool will leverage existing datasets and synthetic data generation techniques. Evaluation metrics will be proposed to assess the performance of GNN models on these datasets. Expected outcomes include improved GNN models and a better understanding of system requirements and performance across different dataset sizes and complexities."} {"type": "action_communicate", "action_name": "communicate_to", "result": "### Summary of Chat History and Next Steps\n\n**Context and Initial Discussion:**\n- **Agent3** initiated a conversation with **Agent5** to seek insights on developing flexible graph datasets with varying graph sizes, embeddings, and homophily levels, along with sufficient labeled data.\n- **Agent3** proposed using synthetic data generation techniques, dataset augmentation, and creating a flexible dataset generation tool. The focus was on maintaining consistency in homophily and embeddings, and developing appropriate evaluation metrics to address the lack of large-scale datasets with sufficient labeled data and to facilitate systematic evaluation of GNN models.\n\n**Next Logical Steps:**\nGiven the detailed analysis and proposed research idea, the next steps are outlined to refine the research proposal and ensure all components are well-defined and feasible:\n\n1. **Refine the Research Proposal:**\n   - **Clarify Objectives:** Define and align research objectives with the problem statement.\n   - **Methodology:** Provide detailed descriptions of methods, including specific algorithms or techniques.\n   - **Dataset:** Specify datasets to be used or generated, including synthetic data generation techniques.\n   - **Evaluation Metrics:** Detail evaluation metrics for assessing GNN model performance.\n\n2. **Literature Review:**\n   - Conduct a thorough literature review to identify relevant work and gaps in existing literature.\n   - Ensure the proposed research idea is well-supported and addresses identified gaps.\n\n3. **Feasibility Study:**\n   - Assess the feasibility of the research, considering resource availability, time constraints, and technical challenges.\n   - Identify potential obstacles and develop strategies to overcome them.\n\n4. **Preliminary Experiments:**\n   - Design and conduct preliminary experiments to validate proposed methods and gather initial results.\n   - Use results to refine methodology and ensure approach viability.\n\n5. **Draft the Research Paper:**\n   - Start drafting the research paper, including sections such as Introduction, Related Work, Methodology, Results, and Conclusion.\n   - Ensure the paper is well-structured and clearly communicates research objectives, methods, and expected outcomes.\n\n6. **Seek Feedback:**\n   - Share the draft with peers or mentors for feedback.\n   - Use feedback to further refine the research proposal and paper.\n\nBy following these steps, the research proposal will be well-defined, feasible, and aligned with the goals outlined in the Introduction."} {"type": "action_function_call", "action_name": "new_communication_session", "args": {"target_agent_id": "agent5", "message": "Ca