is involves creating graph structures that mimic real-world scenarios while allowing for controlled variations in size and density.\n- **Tools:** Use graph generation libraries such as NetworkX and PyTorch Geometric. These libraries provide the necessary tools to create and manipulate graph structures programmatically.\n- **Evaluation:** Ensure that synthetic datasets maintain realistic graph structures and properties. This includes evaluating the degree distribution, clustering coefficient, and other topological features to ensure that the synthetic graphs are representative of real-world data.\n\n#### Data Augmentation Techniques:\n- **Techniques:** Explore techniques such as node attribute perturbation, edge addition/removal, and subgraph sampling. These techniques can increase the diversity and size of labeled datasets by introducing variations in the graph structure and node attributes.\n- **Integration:** Integrate these techniques into existing GNN training pipelines to increase the diversity and size of labeled datasets. This will help improve the robustness and generalization capabilities of the GNN models.\n\n#### Transfer Learning for Graphs:\n- **Methods:** Develop transfer learning methods that leverage pre-trained models on large, unlabeled datasets and fine-tune them on smaller, labeled datasets. This approach can improve the performance of GNNs on multi-label classification tasks by leveraging the knowledge learned from large datasets.\n- **Evaluation:** Assess the effectiveness of these methods in improving GNN performance on multi-label classification tasks. This includes evaluating metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score to ensure that the transfer learning methods are effective.\n\n### Evaluation Metrics:\n- **Accuracy:** Measure the accuracy of the GNN models on the synthetic and augmented datasets.\n- **Precision, Recall, F1-score:** Evaluate the precision, recall, and F1-score to assess the model's performance on multi-label 